728258f-a.folder: Yellowstone Boulevard & Fleet Street, Queens, NY
728258f-a.text:
Yellowstone Avenue (center of the view), between Fleet and Dartmouth Streets showing in the center thereof the Richard Sprague Jr. later the Wm. Boerum house, at the S.E. corner of Dane Place and Exeter Street. At the right foreground is the Abraham Furman house which was demolished in 1923 by fire. The Pennsylvania Railroad became the owner of all the property seen in 1923. View number two shows a clear view of the last mentioned house. It was last remodeled about 1859 or 1860.
April 1923
Views 1 a nd 2
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

728272f-a.folder: Yellowstone Boulevard & Fleet Street, Queens, NY
728272f-a.text:
Yellowstone Boulevard, east side between Fleet and Exeter Streets, showing in 4 views the William Boerum farmhouse of 1852 to 1860. Other owners were Mrs. Boerums Estate, 1873; A Miller, 1873 to 1909; Ed. England owner and subsequent occupant; Pennsylvania Railroad, 1923, and one Weiner an occupant in 1923. The house was still standing in Nov. 1933. See other views.
1922
View 2: April 1923
View 3: March 1925
View 4: Aug. 1925.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

728273f-a.folder: Yellowstone Boulevard & Fleet Street, Queens, NY
728273f-a.text:
Yellowstone Houlevard, south side, east from Fleet Street. The peaked roof house seen in the background is partially in the west street line of Exeter Street, just south of Yellowstone Boulevard. The street actually shown in these views is White Pot Road which subsequently became krown as Dane Place. Tho above named Boulevard has peen constructed at the rigt of Dane Place and junctions it at Exteter Street and from there absorbs it. Ihe farmland and buildings thereon seen in this view were a part
of Mrs. Noerum's Estate in 1873.
March 1925.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection
